WEBVTT

00:01.829 --> 00:05.177
Adult Dean: The Jefferson Davis
Junior High School science fair
was only a couple days away,

00:05.177 --> 00:07.248
and a few of us stayed late
to work on my project.

00:07.248 --> 00:10.596
By 7th grade, I'd taken my game
to the next level.

00:10.596 --> 00:13.599
Then...add a catalyst

00:13.599 --> 00:17.051
and stir and...

00:19.536 --> 00:21.676
Whoa!
Whoa!

00:21.676 --> 00:23.368
[ Laughter ]

00:23.368 --> 00:25.715
Just wait till I make
my own yeast out of potatoes.

00:25.715 --> 00:27.544
Hey, I bet you could win the
science fair this year, Dean.

00:27.544 --> 00:29.236
Me? No.

00:29.236 --> 00:31.203
Of course I was winning.

00:31.203 --> 00:32.894
I'd been doing experiments
ever since my aunt

00:32.894 --> 00:35.173
got me my first chemistry set
when I was 8.

00:35.173 --> 00:37.106
I was still holding out hope
that a lab accident

00:37.106 --> 00:40.557
would bestow me with
superpowers, but no luck yet.

00:40.557 --> 00:42.594
♪♪

00:42.594 --> 00:44.561
Goliath is kinda cool,
huh?

00:44.561 --> 00:47.737
See, in comics, you could be
a nerdand be cool.

00:47.737 --> 00:50.464
Peter Parker, Bruce Banner,
Hank Pym --

00:50.464 --> 00:53.915
all were superheroes that
started out as scientists.

00:53.915 --> 00:56.780
What you doing, nerd?
Reading like you white?

00:56.780 --> 00:58.265
Leave my stuff alone!

00:58.265 --> 01:00.715
Or what, dork?

01:00.715 --> 01:03.442
In that moment, the spirit of
every scientist superhero

01:03.442 --> 01:05.375
coursed through my veins.

01:05.375 --> 01:08.827
Standing before me was the most
evil supervillain ever born,

01:08.827 --> 01:12.141
and I owed it to the world
to do something.

01:12.141 --> 01:14.453
[ Students chanting
"fight, fight" ]
Read! This! Science! Boy!

01:14.453 --> 01:16.835
Hey!
Pick on someone your own size!

01:16.835 --> 01:18.630
You know he can't fight!

01:18.630 --> 01:20.632
Was there anything more
embarrassing than your crush

01:20.632 --> 01:23.531
calling you a wimp in front of
the entire school?

01:23.531 --> 01:26.983
Get off my son!
You know he can't fight!

01:26.983 --> 01:28.674
Yeah. Guess there was.

01:28.674 --> 01:30.883
Mom, what are you doing?
I almost had him.

01:30.883 --> 01:33.369
I did not raise you
to be out here fighting.

01:33.369 --> 01:35.578
What is your name,
young man?

01:35.578 --> 01:37.580
Michael Simms, ma'am.

01:37.580 --> 01:39.168
Back then, there was
an unspoken agreement

01:39.168 --> 01:41.204
that Black parents
were allowed to parent

01:41.204 --> 01:44.483
not just their own kids, but
all the kids in the community.

01:44.483 --> 01:47.176
Both of you,
butts in the car.

01:47.176 --> 01:48.660
Now!

01:48.660 --> 01:51.835
♪♪

01:51.835 --> 01:52.905
♪ Oh, oh, oh

01:52.905 --> 01:53.906
♪ And I know

01:53.906 --> 01:55.770
♪ Ohh

01:55.770 --> 01:57.807
♪ Through the highs
and the lows ♪

01:57.807 --> 02:01.914
♪ I'mma find my way home

02:01.914 --> 02:08.783
♪♪

02:12.132 --> 02:14.030
Unh-unh. You wanna fight?

02:14.030 --> 02:15.618
Then you're gonna have
to pay the piper.

02:15.618 --> 02:17.447
Your parents are gonna wanna
hear about this.

02:17.447 --> 02:19.518
Come on.

02:19.518 --> 02:20.968
Let's go. Come on.

02:25.317 --> 02:26.663
[ Car door closes ]

02:29.287 --> 02:30.978
[ Knock on door ]

02:38.158 --> 02:40.643
Michael,
are your parents home?

02:40.643 --> 02:42.817
Who was supposed
to pick you up?

02:42.817 --> 02:44.474
My brother.

02:44.474 --> 02:47.477
But he usually
has to work late.

02:52.827 --> 02:54.657
Are you home alone?

02:54.657 --> 02:56.693
I-It's fine.

03:08.705 --> 03:10.051
[ Sighs ]

03:10.051 --> 03:15.574
♪♪

03:15.574 --> 03:16.920
[ Car door closes ]

03:20.890 --> 03:23.824
Tell me about your friend
Michael.
He's not my friend.

03:23.824 --> 03:26.585
How do you begin to describe
someone that is so evil,

03:26.585 --> 03:30.210
diabolical, dastardly,
antithetical to everything good

03:30.210 --> 03:31.590
in the world?

03:31.590 --> 03:33.213
He's a butthead.

03:33.213 --> 03:42.636
♪♪

03:42.636 --> 03:44.983
Can you believe
this boy's situation?

03:44.983 --> 03:47.054
I mean, clothes thrown
all across the sofa.

03:47.054 --> 03:48.745
And I'd hate to see
the kitchen.

03:48.745 --> 03:50.920
Probably dishes everywhere.
It's a real shame.

03:50.920 --> 03:53.474
Mm-hmm. And I was talking to
some of the moms --

03:53.474 --> 03:54.820
You mean the mom busybody
gossip line?

03:54.820 --> 03:56.512
[ Laughter ]

03:56.512 --> 03:58.307
Speaking of which,
Miss Doris said

03:58.307 --> 04:01.241
she saw you at the mall,
and I said that was impossible

04:01.241 --> 04:03.484
because you told us
you were at the library.

04:03.484 --> 04:05.245
Keys.

04:05.245 --> 04:06.522
Mm.
[ Keys jingle ]

04:08.558 --> 04:10.491
Now, anyway,
as I was saying,

04:10.491 --> 04:13.908
I found out that Michael's
older brother is 22 years old.

04:13.908 --> 04:15.358
Can you imagine?

04:15.358 --> 04:16.877
A boy being raised
by someone

04:16.877 --> 04:18.913
who's practically
a child himself.

04:18.913 --> 04:20.260
Well, at least
they have each other.

04:20.260 --> 04:22.434
I bet Michael
could use some guidance

04:22.434 --> 04:24.229
and a warm meal, too.

04:24.229 --> 04:26.058
Michael definitely didn't need
another meal.

04:26.058 --> 04:28.647
He was already the size of
a linebacker in 7th grade.

04:28.647 --> 04:30.028
Okay, Lil.

04:30.028 --> 04:32.099
I see where this is going,
and no.

04:32.099 --> 04:33.790
You let that boy in here,
he gonna steal something.

04:33.790 --> 04:35.378
I don't know
what you mean.

04:35.378 --> 04:37.553
You can't fix every baby bird
with a broken wing.

04:37.553 --> 04:39.693
Even if it is Dean's friend.
He's not my friend.

04:39.693 --> 04:41.281
You remember Homeless Joe?

04:41.281 --> 04:43.213
How many batches of hot water
cornbread you bring him?

04:43.213 --> 04:45.354
Still on that stuff.
Well, that ain't
the cornbread's fault.

04:45.354 --> 04:46.803
And what about
your Cousin Joanne

04:46.803 --> 04:48.771
who needed $100
to start that hair salon?

04:48.771 --> 04:50.911
Mm-hmm. Then she met a man
with a Cadillac,

04:50.911 --> 04:52.533
and we never saw her again.

04:52.533 --> 04:54.811
Well, I will not apologize
for being Christ-like.

04:54.811 --> 04:57.227
Hmm. You weren't so Christ-like
when that co-ed from my college

04:57.227 --> 04:59.229
needed a place to stay.
[ Laughs ]

04:59.229 --> 05:01.301
[ Laughs sarcastically ]

05:01.301 --> 05:03.337
What that girl needed
was a job

05:03.337 --> 05:05.132
and a shirt
with a neckline.

05:05.132 --> 05:06.685
Mm-hmm.

05:06.685 --> 05:10.551
Anyway, I'm not gonna be
helping Michael. Dean is.

05:10.551 --> 05:12.001
What? Why me?

05:12.001 --> 05:13.830
Because you said so
yourself.

05:13.830 --> 05:15.660
He doesn't do well
in school,

05:15.660 --> 05:18.145
and look,
we've been blessed with so much,

05:18.145 --> 05:20.043
which is why you do so well.

05:20.043 --> 05:22.287
I think it'd be a good idea
for you to help someone

05:22.287 --> 05:24.254
who's less fortunate.

05:24.254 --> 05:26.256
What my mom was asking
was just as ridiculous

05:26.256 --> 05:29.329
as asking Spider-Man
to team up with Doc Ock.

05:29.329 --> 05:30.813
[ Chuckles] I mean, sure,
it happened once,

05:30.813 --> 05:33.367
but only because Spidey
had amnesia.

05:33.367 --> 05:35.507
Wait, can't I help
Homeless Joe?

05:35.507 --> 05:37.164
I bet he never
finished school.

05:37.164 --> 05:38.199
This is happening.

05:38.199 --> 05:42.411
♪♪

05:49.866 --> 05:51.523
I promised my mom
I'd offer to help Michael.
Sure, I'd been working on
my project for a month

05:51.523 --> 05:52.938
and he hadn't even started his.

05:52.938 --> 05:55.389
That'stotally fair.

05:55.389 --> 05:57.840
My mom says I have to help you
with your science project.

05:57.840 --> 05:59.842
Shut up.

05:59.842 --> 06:01.119
Cool.

06:01.119 --> 06:02.465
Oh, well. I tried.

06:02.465 --> 06:04.674
♪♪

06:04.674 --> 06:06.987
I knew my mom was hoping
I'd try harder,

06:06.987 --> 06:08.920
but there was no way I was
teaming up with a guy

06:08.920 --> 06:12.441
that's been tormenting me since
we were in the 2nd grade.

06:12.441 --> 06:15.582
Oh.
That's Michael Simms

06:15.582 --> 06:17.825
in yourkitchen.

06:17.825 --> 06:19.448
Huh.

06:19.448 --> 06:21.484
Well, it was nice knowing you,
man.

06:21.484 --> 06:24.522
I'm gonna work at my house.
[ Scoffs ]

06:28.871 --> 06:31.701
Mom!
What is he doing here?

06:31.701 --> 06:33.358
I told you he didn't want
my help.

06:33.358 --> 06:36.292
Yes, and I'm sure you asked
very sincerely.

06:36.292 --> 06:38.398
My mother definitely
had my number.

06:38.398 --> 06:41.124
And since I'm not about to let
this boy show up empty-handed,

06:41.124 --> 06:43.126
we decided to make
a potato clock

06:43.126 --> 06:45.370
using one of your old
science kits.

06:45.370 --> 06:47.993
But you're gonna do all the work
yourself, you understand?

06:47.993 --> 06:49.616
Yes, ma'am.

06:49.616 --> 06:51.411
But those are the potatoes
from myproject.

06:51.411 --> 06:53.620
Sweetheart, don't be silly.
There are plenty of potatoes.

06:53.620 --> 06:56.174
Who knew root vegetables
could be so interesting?

06:56.174 --> 06:57.865
Uh, I did.

06:57.865 --> 06:59.453
Michael was just reading about
the role electrolytes

06:59.453 --> 07:02.042
play in conduction,
weren't you?
Yes, ma'am.

07:02.042 --> 07:03.630
Well, alright, then.
Go ahead. Keep reading.

07:03.630 --> 07:05.217
We don't have all year.

07:06.253 --> 07:08.876
"An elec-trolyte

07:08.876 --> 07:11.189
is a soob-sti-nin-a-nence

07:11.189 --> 07:15.780
which e-mits ions when..."

07:15.780 --> 07:17.747
[ Slams table ]
Dangit!

07:17.747 --> 07:19.887
You don't use that language
in school, do you?

07:19.887 --> 07:21.199
Yeah.

07:21.199 --> 07:23.201
I mean, no.

07:23.201 --> 07:24.305
Sorry, ma'am.

07:24.305 --> 07:25.893
Alright.
That's what I thought.

07:25.893 --> 07:27.101
Now, keep going.

07:28.240 --> 07:29.759
I can't.

07:29.759 --> 07:32.659
Listen, you use that word
"can't" one more time,

07:32.659 --> 07:36.076
and not reading will be
the last of your worries.

07:36.076 --> 07:38.734
What was my mother doing?
You don't poke the bear.

07:38.734 --> 07:40.494
She was racking up a swirly tab

07:40.494 --> 07:43.324
that I was gonna have to pay
for tomorrow at school.

07:43.324 --> 07:48.916
♪♪

07:48.916 --> 07:51.505
♪ It's easy to see

07:51.505 --> 07:53.334
♪ You better be

07:53.334 --> 07:55.682
Your mom said I have
to ride the bus home
with you after school.

07:55.682 --> 07:57.477
He was coming back for more?

07:57.477 --> 07:59.513
What type of madman would do
homework with my mother

07:59.513 --> 08:01.308
if they didn't have to?

08:01.308 --> 08:02.482
You're not gonna hit me?

08:04.138 --> 08:05.692
What a weirdo.

08:05.692 --> 08:07.590
[ Groans ]

08:07.590 --> 08:10.248
♪♪

08:10.248 --> 08:12.595
While my mom spent
the last couple of days

08:12.595 --> 08:16.392
working with my archnemesis
on a rudimentary potato clock,

08:16.392 --> 08:18.187
I was working on
splitting oxygen atoms

08:18.187 --> 08:20.223
like a real scientist.

08:20.223 --> 08:22.191
[ Laughter ]
Unfortunately, Michael Simms

08:22.191 --> 08:24.883
was clearly intent on
disrupting my peaceful lair.

08:24.883 --> 08:26.678
Lillian:
That's hilarious, Michael.

08:26.678 --> 08:28.922
Dean never told me
how funny you were.

08:28.922 --> 08:31.096
Well, maybe if I got to drink
beer and watch Richard Pryor,

08:31.096 --> 08:32.753
I'd be funny, too.

08:32.753 --> 08:35.549
Mom loves spending time with her
new favorite son, huh?

08:35.549 --> 08:36.861
Shut up, Kim.

08:36.861 --> 08:38.690
But she had a point.

08:38.690 --> 08:41.037
What if they got so close,
my mom tried to adopt him?

08:41.037 --> 08:46.629
♪♪

08:46.629 --> 08:48.286
Now, don't blow up my house,
son.

08:48.286 --> 08:50.702
♪♪

08:50.702 --> 08:52.152
Now,
wait just a second.

08:52.152 --> 08:54.534
The lighting's better
in here.

08:54.534 --> 08:56.536
Remember to keep them
from touching.

08:56.536 --> 08:57.778
It won't work
if they do.

08:57.778 --> 08:59.953
Which reminds me,
I have to check on

08:59.953 --> 09:01.886
my potato yeast
that I'm making.

09:01.886 --> 09:05.061
By myself. From scratch.

09:05.061 --> 09:07.512
Mrs. Williams,
where do these wires go?

09:07.512 --> 09:10.619
You connect your two potatoes
to the clock?

09:10.619 --> 09:12.137
[ Door opens ]
Mm-hmm.

09:12.137 --> 09:14.554
[ Sighs ] Sorry I'm late.
Then you move those...

09:14.554 --> 09:16.210
Dinner almost ready?

09:16.210 --> 09:18.419
Ooh, I'm so sorry.

09:18.419 --> 09:20.974
We were working so hard, we
completely lost track of time.

09:20.974 --> 09:23.873
At last. The one cardinal sin
in a Black household

09:23.873 --> 09:26.842
is putting someone above
the dad in the food chain.

09:26.842 --> 09:29.016
There's no way my dad
was gonna stand for this.

09:29.016 --> 09:31.018
I'll just heat up leftovers
since you're busy.

09:31.018 --> 09:34.401
Well, that was unexpected,
but at least family dinner

09:34.401 --> 09:36.196
meant Michael
would finally have to go home.

09:36.196 --> 09:38.681
Michael,
it's getting late.

09:38.681 --> 09:40.027
You should stay
for dinner.

09:40.027 --> 09:42.996
Drat. Curses. Zounds.

09:42.996 --> 09:44.894
All that stuff.

09:48.898 --> 09:52.108
Perhaps there's still time
to poison his next course.

09:52.108 --> 09:54.076
Michael,
can I offer you seconds?

09:55.905 --> 09:58.390
Yes, please.

09:58.390 --> 10:01.117
I'll just take bologna
to the office.

10:01.117 --> 10:05.018
Uh, you know, Michael, Kim has
been looking at colleges.

10:05.018 --> 10:07.227
Is that something you might be
interested in doing?

10:09.367 --> 10:11.576
Haven't I seen you hanging
around Jacque's house?

10:11.576 --> 10:13.958
I don't think so.
Yeah.

10:13.958 --> 10:16.132
No, it was definitely you.

10:16.132 --> 10:18.894
Man,
those parties are so loud.

10:18.894 --> 10:20.550
And the kissing.

10:20.550 --> 10:23.346
I've never seen that many people
locking lips in my life.

10:23.346 --> 10:26.039
Keys.
[ Sighs ]

10:30.630 --> 10:32.114
[ Car horn honks ]

10:32.114 --> 10:34.461
Oh.
Must be your brother.

10:34.461 --> 10:36.739
I'm so proud of the work
you did today.

10:36.739 --> 10:39.639
That clock is really
coming along.

10:39.639 --> 10:42.918
You know, if you applied
yourself, one day,

10:42.918 --> 10:46.197
you could become
a really great scientist.

10:46.197 --> 10:47.716
[ Chuckles ]

10:49.994 --> 10:51.374
[ Door opens ]

10:51.374 --> 10:53.756
Thank you,
Mrs. Williams.

10:53.756 --> 10:57.035
Good night.
And good luck tomorrow.

10:57.035 --> 10:58.658
Good night.

11:04.008 --> 11:06.976
[ Sighs ] Well, mm.

11:10.048 --> 11:11.809
This is really great.

11:11.809 --> 11:14.846
♪♪

11:14.846 --> 11:16.054
Hmm.

11:16.054 --> 11:21.335
♪♪

11:21.335 --> 11:23.234
Huh.

11:23.234 --> 11:25.685
Project's coming along
nicely.

11:25.685 --> 11:27.100
I guess.

11:27.100 --> 11:28.895
Is that
a nuclear power plant?

11:28.895 --> 11:31.173
Maybe.

11:31.173 --> 11:32.761
I found your potato water
on the counter.

11:32.761 --> 11:34.521
You want me to put it
in the fridge?

11:34.521 --> 11:36.109
Whatever.

11:36.109 --> 11:37.558
Obviously, I was handling
the situation

11:37.558 --> 11:39.457
with the utmost maturity.

11:39.457 --> 11:42.563
You know, I'm so proud of you
for doing all this on your own.

11:42.563 --> 11:46.878
Yeah, and maybe I'llbecome
a great scientist one day, too.

11:49.743 --> 11:52.125
Okay.

11:54.575 --> 11:56.750
Come here.

12:03.308 --> 12:05.863
I get that this is probably
very uncomfortable for you.

12:05.863 --> 12:08.451
How could you be so nice to
someone who's so mean to me?

12:08.451 --> 12:10.177
[ Sighs ]

12:10.177 --> 12:11.696
Well, the thing you have to
understand is that Michael

12:11.696 --> 12:14.112
hasn't had
an easy life.

12:14.112 --> 12:17.046
You get love from me
and your father every day.

12:17.046 --> 12:19.946
Michael isn't blessed
with that type of love.

12:19.946 --> 12:23.156
There are things he misses out
on that we take for granted.

12:23.156 --> 12:25.192
So, he's allowed
to beat me up?

12:25.192 --> 12:28.955
The reason Michael lashes out
is because he's angry.

12:28.955 --> 12:31.509
What could he possibly be
angry about?

12:31.509 --> 12:34.236
He gets to keep everyone's
lunch money every day.

12:34.236 --> 12:36.376
Well, it's complicated.

12:36.376 --> 12:38.585
I think the big part of it is
the fact that his parents

12:38.585 --> 12:42.209
aren't there to support him
the way we do for you.

12:42.209 --> 12:44.418
Then he shouldn't have
killed them.

12:44.418 --> 12:48.215
[ Scoffs ] He didn't.
Dean.

12:48.215 --> 12:51.253
Michael shared with me that the
reason his mother's not around

12:51.253 --> 12:54.670
is because she's not able
to take care of him.

12:54.670 --> 12:57.569
She had to go into
a mental hospital.

12:57.569 --> 12:59.330
It happened
a few years ago,

12:59.330 --> 13:03.713
when he was around your age,
and he hasn't seen her since.

13:03.713 --> 13:07.441
Oh. That is bad.

13:07.441 --> 13:09.305
Wait, does that mean

13:09.305 --> 13:10.755
if something happens
to you and Dad,

13:10.755 --> 13:12.239
I have to live with Kim?
[ Sighs ]

13:12.239 --> 13:14.759
First off, nothing is gonna
happen to us,

13:14.759 --> 13:17.797
but it's important
to put yourself in
someone else's shoes.

13:17.797 --> 13:19.799
That's why I helped him.

13:19.799 --> 13:22.629
I can't imagine how hard
his life must be.

13:22.629 --> 13:24.148
Does that make sense?

13:27.082 --> 13:29.670
Right.

13:29.670 --> 13:32.984
And I hope you remember that
I'll always be proud of you.

13:32.984 --> 13:35.849
Now, get some rest.
Got a big day tomorrow.

13:37.644 --> 13:39.577
Good night.
Good night, Mom.

13:39.577 --> 13:44.271
♪♪

13:44.271 --> 13:46.170
Despite the years of bullying,

13:46.170 --> 13:48.275
I found myself genuinely
feeling sorry

13:48.275 --> 13:50.830
for Michael and his mom.

13:50.830 --> 13:53.246
Pretty sure he still killed
his father, though.

13:59.321 --> 14:01.047
Ah, the science fair.
One of the best days of
the year, next to Christmas,

14:01.047 --> 14:04.015
my birthday, and Mama's
short rib Sundays, of course.

14:04.015 --> 14:06.362
Carrol, how's it going?
Hey, Tom, good luck.

14:06.362 --> 14:08.744
You're gonna need it.
Just kidding.

14:08.744 --> 14:11.574
♪♪

14:11.574 --> 14:13.749
The boy ain't right.
Oh, shush.

14:13.749 --> 14:16.579
So, you feeling confident?

14:16.579 --> 14:17.960
A little.

14:17.960 --> 14:19.548
A little? Please.

14:19.548 --> 14:21.446
I was gonna win this thing
hands down.

14:21.446 --> 14:23.138
I mean,
look at the competition.

14:23.138 --> 14:25.381
A baking soda volcano?

14:25.381 --> 14:27.107
What are we, in 2nd grade?

14:27.107 --> 14:29.696
♪♪

14:29.696 --> 14:31.629
Oobleck? Wow.

14:31.629 --> 14:33.148
You mixed corn starch
and water.

14:33.148 --> 14:35.771
Did you do that yourself?
Heh.

14:35.771 --> 14:37.980
Why is Neptune bigger
than Jupiter?

14:37.980 --> 14:39.602
Come on, Larry.

14:39.602 --> 14:41.604
Everyone knows
it's seven times smaller.

14:41.604 --> 14:43.779
If I'm looking at
the future of NASA,

14:43.779 --> 14:46.161
then the Russians have nothing
to worry about.

14:46.161 --> 14:48.646
Hey, Dean, check it out.

14:48.646 --> 14:50.820
I painted my shoe box so it
looks like an actual oven.

14:50.820 --> 14:52.892
Cool, right?

14:57.068 --> 14:58.725
Michael: S-Sorry,
sorry, sorry.

14:58.725 --> 15:00.347
Michael.

15:00.347 --> 15:02.384
I'm glad you made it.
Everything okay?

15:02.384 --> 15:04.144
Yes, ma'am.

15:06.664 --> 15:08.908
Hey.

15:08.908 --> 15:10.979
Good luck.

15:10.979 --> 15:13.498
Thanks.

15:13.498 --> 15:16.501
You know, Lil, in spite
of my concerns, I got to admit,

15:16.501 --> 15:19.194
you were right
this time.

15:19.194 --> 15:20.678
Wait, is that my shirt?

15:20.678 --> 15:22.852
I knew he was gonna steal
something.

15:22.852 --> 15:24.233
See, you can't help
some people.

15:24.233 --> 15:26.166
I gave him the shirt,
Bill.

15:26.166 --> 15:27.857
He didn't have any good clothes
to wear.

15:27.857 --> 15:29.721
Besides, you haven't worn
that thing in years.

15:29.721 --> 15:32.310
And like I said,
you were very wise.

15:32.310 --> 15:37.764
♪♪

15:37.764 --> 15:39.835
Michael,
this looks interesting.

15:39.835 --> 15:41.492
Did you do this
all on your own?

15:41.492 --> 15:44.426
Um, I had some help.

15:44.426 --> 15:46.842
Can you tell us about
your project?

15:46.842 --> 15:49.258
Um,
it's a potato clock.

15:49.258 --> 15:50.259
And how does it work?

15:50.259 --> 15:52.261
Uh, it tells the time?

15:52.261 --> 15:53.676
[ Chuckles ]
The science, son.

15:53.676 --> 15:55.092
Oh.

15:55.092 --> 15:58.509
Um, well, the potatoes
have acid,

15:58.509 --> 16:01.477
which eats the nail,

16:01.477 --> 16:05.654
and that makes...
electrons.

16:08.795 --> 16:11.280
The penny then picks up
the electrons,

16:11.280 --> 16:13.179
and that makes
electricity.

16:13.179 --> 16:15.353
Oh.

16:15.353 --> 16:17.459
Can't wait to see you
apply yourself like
this in the classroom.

16:17.459 --> 16:20.393
Even if it was a low bar,
I was happy for Michael.

16:20.393 --> 16:22.464
It was the first time
I'd seen him smile

16:22.464 --> 16:24.293
when he wasn't beating
somebody up.

16:24.293 --> 16:26.019
Let's just hope he remembered
that other things

16:26.019 --> 16:27.400
could make him happy.

16:27.400 --> 16:28.849
[ Sighs ]
Our future scientist.

16:28.849 --> 16:30.196
What have you made
for us?

16:30.196 --> 16:31.576
Today, I will be
demonstrating

16:31.576 --> 16:33.785
the principles
of a nuclear fission reactor

16:33.785 --> 16:35.546
with a dash of pizzazz.

16:35.546 --> 16:37.306
Nuclear power plants
generate heat

16:37.306 --> 16:39.343
by splitting unstable
uranium atoms.

16:39.343 --> 16:41.690
In my experiment,
I will be creating a similar

16:41.690 --> 16:44.210
exothermic reaction
by splitting oxygen

16:44.210 --> 16:46.143
and unstable
hydrogen peroxide

16:46.143 --> 16:48.179
with potato yeast
I made myself.

16:48.179 --> 16:49.525
Safety first, though.

16:49.525 --> 16:51.182
You never know
when there's gonna be

16:51.182 --> 16:53.150
a cool nuclear meltdown
of radioactive foam.

17:03.298 --> 17:04.954
Just a moment.

17:04.954 --> 17:07.336
You know, uh, potato yeast
can be a slow catalyst.

17:07.336 --> 17:09.407
[ Students murmuring ]

17:09.407 --> 17:11.996
Maybe it just needs
a good stir.

17:18.589 --> 17:20.970
Uh, the ratios are probably
a little off.

17:20.970 --> 17:24.146
Uh, maybe I need a little bit
more hydrogen peroxide.

17:26.942 --> 17:30.290
As my nuclear reactor turned
into a sad swamp,

17:30.290 --> 17:32.154
I realized that I had been
so distracted

17:32.154 --> 17:33.707
by my mother and Michael

17:33.707 --> 17:35.675
that I hadn't made
my yeast properly.

17:35.675 --> 17:37.159
Ta-da?

17:37.159 --> 17:38.850
[ Giggling ]

17:38.850 --> 17:41.370
My yeast
must have died.

17:41.370 --> 17:43.855
Shame. I was really excited
for this one.

17:43.855 --> 17:46.962
[ Laughter ]
I guess science is about
failure, too.

17:46.962 --> 17:49.999
I had never known this level of
embarrassment before.

17:49.999 --> 17:53.106
Science was my thing.
How could I let this happen?

17:53.106 --> 17:56.385
[ Laughter ]

17:59.975 --> 18:02.081
I don't know what
you're laughing at.

18:02.081 --> 18:04.359
At least I did
my project by myself.

18:04.359 --> 18:05.946
You needed help
from my mom

18:05.946 --> 18:08.087
because your mom is so crazy,
she got locked up.

18:08.087 --> 18:12.021
[ Laughter ]

18:12.021 --> 18:21.445
♪♪

18:21.445 --> 18:23.930
I'd finally vanquished
the supervillain,

18:23.930 --> 18:25.932
so why did it feel like
I had lost?

18:28.555 --> 18:32.352
Wait a minute.
WasI actually the villain?

18:32.352 --> 18:35.079
♪♪

18:35.079 --> 18:38.289
As kids, we don't pause to
think that every supervillain

18:38.289 --> 18:40.947
probably has
a complicated backstory.

18:43.122 --> 18:45.676
And that superheroes don't
always do the right thing.

18:47.850 --> 18:49.818
Or that there are some things
in this world that hurt

18:49.818 --> 18:52.821
even more than getting beat up.

18:52.821 --> 18:56.411
♪♪

18:56.411 --> 18:57.757
[ Thunder rumbles ]

18:57.757 --> 19:04.798
♪♪

19:04.798 --> 19:11.736
♪♪

19:11.736 --> 19:18.743
♪♪

19:18.743 --> 19:22.091
They announced the winner
of the science fair.

19:22.091 --> 19:24.922
I didn't even make it
into the top three.

19:24.922 --> 19:27.890
♪♪

19:27.890 --> 19:30.030
I know
I didn't deserve to win.

19:33.068 --> 19:35.898
No, you didn't.

19:35.898 --> 19:37.797
God don't like ugly,
Dean.

19:37.797 --> 19:40.213
Yikes. I guess that
business-casual belt

19:40.213 --> 19:43.216
was also a Lasso of Truth,
but I had it coming.

19:43.216 --> 19:45.425
How you treat people
comes back around.

19:45.425 --> 19:46.530
Remember that.

19:47.565 --> 19:49.222
I'm really sorry.

19:49.222 --> 19:50.706
I expect you'll find a way
to say that

19:50.706 --> 19:52.467
to Michael one day, too.

19:54.296 --> 19:55.746
Yes, ma'am.

20:03.961 --> 20:07.275
I figure you'd want to start
practicing for next year.

20:07.275 --> 20:09.242
Thank you.

20:09.242 --> 20:12.245
All my mom wanted to do was
help someone less fortunate,

20:12.245 --> 20:13.902
and I ruined it.

20:13.902 --> 20:16.491
I wasn't a superhero at all,

20:16.491 --> 20:19.287
but if I kept my head down
and watched closely,

20:19.287 --> 20:22.635
I had the chance to learn
from an actual superhero --

20:22.635 --> 20:24.257
my mom.

20:24.257 --> 20:26.570
Maybe one day,
in an alternate universe,

20:26.570 --> 20:28.572
she'll have her own storyline.

20:28.572 --> 20:30.332
Hopefully, it'll be
a rare reboot

20:30.332 --> 20:32.645
that's better than
the original.

20:36.165 --> 20:42.931
Finally found a box big enough.
Goodwill will be very happy.
I'm very proud of you, son.

20:43.725 --> 20:46.106
I found a few more shirts
I'm not gonna use anymore.

20:48.902 --> 20:50.973
Wh--
That's my lucky belt.

20:50.973 --> 20:53.976
Mnh-mnh. Trust me,
I'm doing you a favor.

20:53.976 --> 20:56.151
But as disappointed as I was
in myself,

20:56.151 --> 20:58.533
the fact is in all comic book
stories,

20:58.533 --> 21:01.398
every great failure sets up
a sequel where the hero

21:01.398 --> 21:03.434
gets a chance
to redeem himself.

21:03.434 --> 21:06.057
He just needs to take that
first step forward.

21:06.057 --> 21:09.854
♪♪

21:09.854 --> 21:11.856
-- Captions by VITAC --
